Housing prices - forests & deep nets¶

Objectives

  • implement a data pipeline for the data set
  • check differences between the kaggle data set and the train data set (e.g. is there an important date range difference?)
  • set up forest based models with an accuracy of $\approx$ 0.12
  • set up deep net based models with an accuracy of $\approx$ 0.12
  • make predictions over the test set
  • submit predictions over the test set to kaggle to see if the score deviates

General competition info

  • Loss = root mean squared log error
  • dependent variabl = SalePrice
  • 80 other columns available

def kaggle_loss(pred, truth):
    if isinstance(pred, np.ndarray) and isinstance(truth, np.ndarray):
        return np.sqrt(((np.log(pred) - np.log(truth))**2).mean())
    elif isinstance(pred, torch.Tensor) and isinstance(truth, torch.Tensor):
        return torch.sqrt(((torch.log(pred.float()) - torch.log(truth.float()))**2).mean())
    else:
        raise NotImplementedError

def plot_compare_hist(df_train, df_test, col, nbins:int=50):
    
    diff = np.setdiff1d(df_test[col].values, df_train[col].values)
    print(f"\n{col}:\n\tTest set values not found in the training set: {len(diff[~np.isnan(diff)])}, has nan = {np.isnan(diff).any()}, values = {diff[~np.isnan(diff)]}")
    print(f"\ttraining set: min = {df_train[col].min()} max = {df_train[col].max()}")
    print(f"\ttest set: min = {df_test[col].min()} max = {df_test[col].max()}")
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,4))
    bins = np.linspace(df_test[col].min(), df_test[col].max(), nbins)
    ax.hist(df_train[col], bins=bins, label="train", alpha=.5)
    ax.hist(df_test[col], bins=bins, label="test", alpha=.5)
    ax.legend(title="Set")
    ax.set_title(f"{col} frequencies: train vs test")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

transformations = {}  # key = data frame column, value = function to call which needs the data frame passed and returns a new data frame
cont_names = []
cat_names = []

class Transformations:
        
    def __init__(self, df):
        self.df = copy.deepcopy(df)

def change_type(self, col, _type):
    self.df[col] = self.df[col].astype(_type)
    return self

def flag_na(self, col):
    ix = self.df[col].isna()
    if sum(ix)>0:
        na_col = f"{col}_na"
        if na_col in self.df.columns:
            ix = np.logical_or(ix, self.df[na_col])
        self.df[na_col] = ix
    return self

def fill_missing(self, col, fill=None):
    assert fill is not None
    
    ix = self.df[col].isna().values
    if sum(ix) > 0:
        self.df.loc[ix, col] = fill
    return self
    

Transformations.change_type = change_type
Transformations.flag_na = flag_na
Transformations.fill_missing = fill_missing

def _execute(self, fun, col, **kwargs):
    getattr(self, fun)(col=col, **kwargs)
    return self

def execute_single_col_transformations(self, transformations, col, return_df:bool=False):
    for (fun, kwargs) in transformations[col]:
        self._execute(fun, col, **kwargs)
    if return_df: return self.df

def execute_all_transformations(self, transformations, return_df:bool=False, cols2skip:list=None):
    
    for col in sorted(transformations):
        if cols2skip is not None and col not in cols2skip:
            self.execute_single_col_transformations(transformations, col)
        
    if return_df: return self.df
                                
Transformations._execute = _execute
Transformations.execute_single_col_transformations = execute_single_col_transformations
Transformations.execute_all_transformations = execute_all_transformations

def set_greater_values_nan(self, col, threshold):
    ix = self.df[col] > threshold
    if ix.sum()>0:
        self.df.loc[ix, col] = np.nan
        na_col = f"{col}_na"
        if na_col in self.df.columns:
            ix = np.logical_or(ix, self.df[na_col])
        self.df[na_col] = ix
    return self

Let's just make everything that is of string type to a categorical type, applying one hot encoding if the cardinality of the column is lower than max_cardinality.

def make_categorical(self, col, max_cardinality:int=7, fill_na="missing", cats=None):
    
    assert self.df[col].dtype.name == "object"
    
    vals = self.df[col].values
    ix_na = self.df[col].isna().values
    hasna = ix_na.sum()
    cats = np.sort(np.unique(vals[~ix_na])) if cats is None else cats
    
    if hasna:
        vals[ix_na] = fill_na
        na_col = f"{col}_na"
        if na_col in self.df.columns:
            ix_na = np.logical_or(self.df[na_col], ix_na)
        self.df[na_col] = ix_na
    
    cats = np.concatenate(([fill_na], cats)) if fill_na not in cats else cats
    
    cardinality = len(cats)
    if cardinality <= max_cardinality:
        self.df = pd.get_dummies(self.df, prefix=col, columns=[col])
    else:
        self.df[col] = pd.Categorical(vals, categories=cats, ordered=True)
    return self
    
Transformations.make_categorical = make_categorical

Let's repeat the train/valid splitting and fitting n_rep times to see how stable our loss is

n_rep = 7

def repeated_model_training(model, model_params, df, y, train_pct:float=.8, n_rep:int=7):
    losses = np.zeros(n_rep)

    for i in range(n_rep):
        ix_train, ix_valid = get_split_idx(len(df), train_pct=train_pct)
        m = model(**model_params)
        
        m.fit(df.iloc[ix_train], y[ix_train])

        y_pred = m.predict(df.iloc[ix_valid])
        y_ref = y[ix_valid]
        losses[i] = kaggle_loss(y_pred, y_ref.values)

    text = f"mean loss = {losses.mean():.4f}, std loss = {losses.std():.4f}, "\
           f"min loss = {losses.min():.4f}, max loss = {losses.max():.4f}"
    print(text)

def get_partial_dependence_data(model, df: pd.DataFrame, cols, num_samples:int=None):
    if num_samples >= len(df): num_samples = None
    dependencies = {
        col: {
            "ins": sorted(df[col].unique()),
            "freqs": df[col].value_counts().sort_index().values,
            "outs": np.zeros((df[col].nunique(), len(df) if num_samples is None else num_samples))
        }
        for col in cols
    }
    
    for col in cols:
        tmp = df.copy(deep=True)
        if num_samples is not None: tmp = df.loc[np.random.choice(np.arange(len(df)), size=num_samples)]
        for i, val in enumerate(dependencies[col]["ins"]):
            tmp[col] = val
            dependencies[col]["outs"][i] = model.predict(tmp)
    return dependencies
    
deps = get_partial_dependence_data(m, _df, ["LotArea", "YearBuilt", "GrLivArea"], num_samples=100)

%%time
def plot_ICE(deps, centered:bool=False):
    # https://christophm.github.io/interpretable-ml-book/ice.html#ice
    
    deps = copy.deepcopy(deps)
    
    for col in sorted(deps):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
        x = deps[col]["ins"]
        median = np.median(deps[col]["outs"][0])
        for i,y in enumerate(deps[col]["outs"].T):
            if centered:
                y[0] = 0
                y[1:] -= median
            ax.plot(x, y, '-', color="blue", linewidth=.1, alpha=.5)
        
        y_m = np.median(deps[col]["outs"], axis=1)
        if centered: y_m[0] = 0
        ax.plot(x, y_m, "-", color="black", lw=5)
        ax.plot(x, y_m, "-", color="yellow", lw=3)
        ax.scatter(x, np.ones_like(x)*deps[col]["outs"].min(), marker="|", color="black", s=deps[col]["freqs"]*50)
        ax.set_xlabel(f"Dependence: {col}", fontsize=14)
        ylabel = f"Predicted variable" if not centered else f"Predicted variable at {median:.3f}"
        ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=14)
        ax.set_title(f"predicted vs {col}", fontsize=18)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
